{{Pakistani cuisine}}
'''Balochi cuisine''' refers to the food and cuisine of the [[Baloch people]] from the [[Balochistan (region)|Balochistan region]], comprising the [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Pakistani Balochistan]] province, the [[Sistan and Baluchestan Province]] in Iran and [[Balochistan, Afghanistan]]. Baloch food has a regional variance in contrast to the many cuisines of Pakistan<ref name=pakistantumhetoho>{{cite web|title=Baloch Cuisine|url=http://www.pakistantumhetoho.com.pk/BalochCuisine|publisher=pakistantumhetoho.com|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=balochculture>{{cite web|title=Food {{!}} Baloch Culture|url=http://balochculture.net/2013/03/12/theeni-naan/|publisher=balochculture.net|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref> and Iran.

== List of Balochi dishes ==
Prominent Baloch dishes, such as the lamb-skewed [[Sajji]], have gained massive popularity among different parts of Pakistan including the [[food hubs]] of [[Karachi]] and [[Lahore]]. [[Kaak]], a rock-hard prepared bread, and is often served with Sajji.

[[Dampukht]] is also a Balochi dish which is prepared with meat and it's cooked in fats.<ref name="subrung">{{cite web|title=Unique Quetta Cuisine|url=http://www.subrung.com/travel-pakistan/quetta/unique-quetta-cuisine.html|publisher=subrung.com|accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>

Khaddi Kabbab is a dish in which Balochistanis cook a whole lamb or goat over a fire. Usually there is raw rice in the stomach of the lamb and the rice is cooked by the fats of the lamb. The lamb is cooked over a fire.

A large number of Baloch people living on the coastal belt eat fish in their own style.

