{{Infobox language |name=Naŋa dama |nativename=Naŋa tegu |region=[[Mali]] |speakers=3,000 |date=2009 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Dogon languages|Dogon]] |fam3=Nanga–Walo |iso3=nzz |glotto=nang1261 |glottorefname=Nanga }} '''Naŋa dama''', also known as '''Naŋa tegu''', is a [[Dogon language]] spoken in [[Mali]] that is only known from one report from 1953. Roger Blench reports that its nearest relative is the recently described [[Walo–Kumbe Dogon]], "with which it shares both lexicon and the feature that many nouns have a final -m." Hochstetler thinks they may be the same language. It may be close to [[Yanda Dogon]] (Blench) or [[Jam sai dialect|Jamsai tegu]] (Hochstetler).
