'''Transferable development rights''' (TDR) is a method for controlling land use to complement [[land-use planning]] and [[zoning]] for more effective urban growth management and land conservation. The TDR process can be considered a tool for controlling [[urban sprawl]] by concentrating development. TDR is a legal mechanism offered in some local government jurisdictions as a form of [[land development|development]] control. The procedure offers landowners financial incentives or bonuses for the conservation and maintenance of the environmental, heritage or agricultural values of their land. TDR is based on the concept that with land ownership comes the right of use of land, or [[land development]]. These land-based development rights can in some jurisdictions be used, unused, sold, or otherwise transferred by the owner of a parcel.<ref name="Handbook">{{cite book |last1=Nelson |first1=Arthur C. |last2=Pruetz |first2=Rick |last3=Woodruff |first3=Doug |year=2011 |title=The TDR Handbook: Designing and Implementing Transfer of Development Rights Programs |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Island Press |isbn=9781610911597}}</ref>{{rp|3}} <ref name="Farmland Trust">{{cite web |url=http://www.farmland.org//programs/states/wa/documents/APPENDIXH-Transferofdevelopmentrights.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116082248/http://www.farmland.org//programs/states/wa/documents/APPENDIXH-Transferofdevelopmentrights.pdf |title=Transfer of Development Rights; Fact Sheet |date=April 2008 |archive-date=2011-01-16 |publisher=American Farmland Trust |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>
Developers can purchase the development rights of certain parcels within a designated "sending district" and transfer the rights to another "receiving district" to increase the density of their new development. Alternatively, parcels with buildings that do not use all of their available size have "excess" developable capacity that can be conveyed to other parcels, possibly adjoining the first parcels. A widely-noted example of districted TDRs is the [[Montgomery County, Maryland Agricultural Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://montgomeryplanning.org/planning/agricultural-reserve/ |title=Agricultural Reserve |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018-02-23 |publisher=Montgomery County Planning Department |location=Silver Spring, Maryland}}</ref> TDR programs have been implemented in over 200 U.S. communities,<ref name="Handbook"/>{{rp|25}} in several states, including [[Colorado]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bouldercounty.org/property-and-land/land-use/planning/transferable-development-rights-tdr/ |title=Transferable Development Rights Program |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Property & Land |publisher=Boulder County, Colorado |access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref>, [[Massachusetts]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mass.gov/service-details/case-studies-transfer-of-development-rights-tdr |title=Case Studies — Transfer of Development Rights |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Energy and Environmental Affairs |publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts |access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>, [[Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Lloyd, Jr. |first=T. Preston |url=http://www.williamsmullen.com/news/transfer-development-rights-virginia-tapping-market-land-use-entitlements |title=Transfer of Development Rights in Virginia: Tapping into a Market for Land Use Entitlements |date=2012-09-07 |publisher=Williams Mulllen |location=Richmond, VA}}</ref> and [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/services/environment/stewardship/sustainable-building/transfer-development-rights.aspx |title=Transfer of development rights in King County, Washington |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2016-11-29 |website=Sustainable building |publisher=King County, Washington}}</ref> Receiving districts are generally areas more suited for higher density developments and sending districts are areas with environmental, heritage or agricultural values that the county, city or town wishes to preserve.<ref>[http://www.mass.gov/envir/smart_growth_toolkit/pages/mod-tdr.html] Massachusetts Smart Growth/Smart Energy Toolkit "Transfer of Development Rights (TDR)"</ref>
TDR credit banks can be used to store development rights that have been purchased if there is not yet a receiving area development identified. This mechanism is used when the time of the sale in the sending area is not concurrent with a development in the receiving area. It is also useful in communities that have the opportunity to purchase the rights from an area of high conservation interest but do not have a development that can receive higher density at the time. TDR credit banks should be operated by a third party organization that is empowered to negotiate the sale of development rights such as a non-profit organization or an agency operating within the community.<ref>Massachusetts Executive Office of Energy and Environmental Affairs, [http://www.mass.gov/envir/smart_growth_toolkit/bylaws/TDR-Bylaw.pdf "Transfer of Development Rights"] Massachusetts Smart Growth/Smart Energy Toolkit Bylaw, 2005. (Feb 1, 2011)</ref>
